```json
// hospitals collection â€” buildings and departments embedded (no $lookup needed to read them)
{
  "hospital_id": "uuid",
  "name": "string",
  "buildings": [
    { "building_id": "uuid", "name": "string", "year": "int" }
  ],
  "departments": [
    {
      "department_id": "uuid",
      "specialty": "string",
      "n_beds": "int",
      "head_physician_id": "uuid",
      "persons": [
        // embedded â€” a department can have many persons working for it.
        // Note: if a person works for multiple departments, their data is
        // duplicated across departments (denormalized on purpose, no $lookup).
        { "p_id": "uuid", "email": "string", "role": "string" }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

Buildings and Departments are embedded arrays inside their parent Hospital (1:N, bounded, always read together with the hospital); Persons are embedded inside each Department they work for, with the `role` attribute (from `Works For`) stored directly on the embedded person subdocument. This achieves 1-hop reads for all four entities without any `$lookup`, at the cost of duplicating a person's data if they work in more than one department.

```js
db.hospitals.aggregate([
  { $addFields: { building_count: { $size: "$buildings" } } },
  { $match: { building_count: { $gt: 10 } } },
  { $addFields: {
      big_departments: {
        $filter: {
          input: "$departments",
          as: "d",
          cond: { $gt: [{ $size: "$$d.persons" }, 25] }
        }
      }
  } },
  { $project: {
      _id: 0,
      hospital_id: 1,
      name: 1,
      departments_over_25: { $size: "$big_departments" }
  } }
])
```

The pipeline first computes each hospital's building count and filters (`$match`) to hospitals with more than 10, then uses `$filter` to keep only departments whose embedded `persons` array has more than 25 elements, and finally projects the count of such departments per hospital.

```js
db.hospitals.aggregate([
  { $unwind: "$departments" },
  { $unwind: "$departments.persons" },
  { $match: { "departments.persons.role": "maintenance" } },
  { $group: {
      _id: "$departments.persons.p_id",
      department_count: { $sum: 1 }
  } },
  { $sort: { department_count: -1 } },
  { $limit: 10 }
])
```

`$unwind` twice to flatten hospitals â†’ departments â†’ persons into one document per (department, person) pair, `$match` on role, then `$group` by person id counting how many department-documents they appear in (equivalent to "how many departments they work for", assuming the same person's `p_id` is duplicated once per department per the embedding design from Exercise 6).
